00:46:32.960 --> 00:46:34.950
JORDAN: Hello.

00:46:34.950 --> 00:46:38.740
What's the relationship
between focus and creativity?

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:41.400
Often, if I pour all my
focus into a problem,

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:43.000
I fail to see better
solutions that

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.605
are obvious when
stepping back a bit.

00:46:45.605 --> 00:46:47.480
DANIEL GOLEMAN: Yeah,
you named the solution.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:50.110
Actually, it's the good
side of this state.

00:46:50.110 --> 00:46:51.580
It's daydreaming.

00:46:51.580 --> 00:46:56.130
Because the classical stages
in solving a creative problem

00:46:56.130 --> 00:47:00.590
are begin with focusing,
with effort, and gathering

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:02.690
all the information, trying
out all the solutions

00:47:02.690 --> 00:47:03.750
you can think of.

00:47:03.750 --> 00:47:06.072
And if you're still
baffled, you let it go.

00:47:06.072 --> 00:47:06.780
And you daydream.

00:47:06.780 --> 00:47:08.800
You go for a walk.

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:10.610
You take a shower.

00:47:10.610 --> 00:47:12.740
The annals of
science and math are

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:15.550
full of instants where--
for example, a mathematician

00:47:15.550 --> 00:47:20.120
grappled with an equation for
years, could not solve it,

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:23.860
and the answer came to him
as he was getting on a bus.

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:29.980
Because in that day-dreamy state
where your mind is wandering,

00:47:29.980 --> 00:47:32.980
you have more access
to the bottom-up part

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:36.750
of the mind, which, remember,
registers everything you know.

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:39.120
And that can put together
two discrete elements that

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:41.080
have never been
combined, but that

00:47:41.080 --> 00:47:44.530
operates in a useful way,
which is a creative product.

00:47:44.530 --> 00:47:46.740
Then, of course, you have
to focus again to execute.

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:50.810
That's another-- I mean,
then you need venture capital

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:52.720
and oh my god, it's
like a headache.

00:47:52.720 --> 00:47:55.639
Did you have another
question, Jordan?

00:47:55.639 --> 00:47:56.180
JORDAN: Yeah.

00:47:56.180 --> 00:47:58.304
Can you give us the
top three points

00:47:58.304 --> 00:47:59.720
from the "Harvard
Business Review"

00:47:59.720 --> 00:48:04.000
article on leadership
and focus, please?

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:07.510
DANIEL GOLEMAN: That's
what my whole talk was.

00:48:07.510 --> 00:48:11.390
It was that leaders need
the three kinds of focus--

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:14.940
inner focus to manage
yourself and lead yourself,

00:48:14.940 --> 00:48:18.530
other focus to read
other people effectively

00:48:18.530 --> 00:48:21.020
and to be able to communicate
in a way which is persuasive,

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:24.840
and that motivates and that
has the right impact-- I mean,

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:26.340
you could say the
art of leadership

00:48:26.340 --> 00:48:30.720
is helping people get
and stay in this state.

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:33.040
And the third is the
systems awareness,

00:48:33.040 --> 00:48:35.660
because you need that
for strategic thinking,

00:48:35.660 --> 00:48:36.200
for example.

00:48:36.200 --> 00:48:37.825
You need to understand
what's happening

00:48:37.825 --> 00:48:38.880
with the technologies.

00:48:38.880 --> 00:48:41.740
You need to understand what's
happening with the economy.

00:48:41.740 --> 00:48:44.990
You need to understand
the larger systems

00:48:44.990 --> 00:48:46.870
that your organization
operates in.

00:48:46.870 --> 00:48:52.390
And so, for example, with
the economic problem,

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:55.110
a lot of companies
promoted people

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:56.910
who were very good at
getting the numbers

00:48:56.910 --> 00:48:59.075
but really trampled on people.

00:48:59.075 --> 00:49:02.830
And now they're realizing
that that lack of empathy

00:49:02.830 --> 00:49:04.920
is costing organizations.

00:49:04.920 --> 00:49:07.920
So what I'm arguing is
that leaders need all three

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:09.650
in balance.

00:49:09.650 --> 00:49:10.620
Will that do?

00:49:10.620 --> 00:49:13.230
JORDAN: One more.

00:49:13.230 --> 00:49:17.100
People with ADD are told that
they are most effective when

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:20.090
they follow their impulses,
instead of forcing themselves

00:49:20.090 --> 00:49:22.970
to control their attention
in a top-down manner.

00:49:22.970 --> 00:49:25.760
How does this fit
into your model?

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:29.390
DANIEL GOLEMAN: So ADD is a
big problem during the school

00:49:29.390 --> 00:49:31.880
years, when there's
a premium on being

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:34.760
able to focus on what the
teacher's saying and so on.

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:38.220
ADD also means
that people's minds

00:49:38.220 --> 00:49:41.150
wander more, which is why it's
a problem during the school

00:49:41.150 --> 00:49:41.890
years.

00:49:41.890 --> 00:49:44.270
But it turns out that
people with ADD tend on,

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:47.690
average, to be more
creative than other people.

00:49:47.690 --> 00:49:52.354
They are more naturally
entrepreneurs, for example.

00:49:52.354 --> 00:49:54.020
JORDAN: Does anyone
else have questions?

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:56.050
DANIEL GOLEMAN: Someone's
behind you here.

00:49:56.050 --> 00:49:58.930
AUDIENCE: So my question
is about cognitive control.

00:49:58.930 --> 00:50:01.020
And you mentioned
a lot of studies

00:50:01.020 --> 00:50:03.570
where certain children
or certain people

00:50:03.570 --> 00:50:05.880
had better cognitive
control than others.

00:50:05.880 --> 00:50:08.449
And my question is, what
factors affect that?

00:50:08.449 --> 00:50:10.490
Do you think it's something
people are born with?

00:50:10.490 --> 00:50:14.160
And is it affected by things
like their socioeconomic

00:50:14.160 --> 00:50:17.830
situation, by culture,
by the education

00:50:17.830 --> 00:50:19.050
they've already received?

00:50:19.050 --> 00:50:20.180
DANIEL GOLEMAN: All of it.

00:50:20.180 --> 00:50:24.320
In other words,
it's both something

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:29.370
that people have some level
of naturally-- it's innate.

00:50:29.370 --> 00:50:30.230
It's genetic.

00:50:30.230 --> 00:50:33.180
But you know, the brain
is plastic through life.

00:50:33.180 --> 00:50:35.250
And the centers for
cognitive control

00:50:35.250 --> 00:50:38.720
are part of the brain that's the
last to develop anatomically--

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:41.380
doesn't mature
fully till mid 20s.

00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:44.190
And during that period of
plasticity, roughly childhood

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:47.940
and adolescence, what you
learn, and systematic training,

00:50:47.940 --> 00:50:49.500
has enormous effect.

00:50:49.500 --> 00:50:53.230
So the basic repetition
for cognitive control

00:50:53.230 --> 00:50:55.734
is you focus on one
thing, your mind wanders,

00:50:55.734 --> 00:50:57.650
you notice it wandered,
and you bring it back.

00:50:57.650 --> 00:50:59.220
Does that sound familiar?

00:50:59.220 --> 00:51:04.430
And every time you do that,
the neurons for that circuitry

00:51:04.430 --> 00:51:06.440
strengthen in
their connectivity.

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:09.900
It's exactly analogous to being
in a gym and lifting weights.

00:51:09.900 --> 00:51:11.410
And every time you
do a repetition,

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:13.510
that muscle gets
a little stronger.

00:51:13.510 --> 00:51:16.690
So the more we can
help children and teens

00:51:16.690 --> 00:51:18.330
do that-- which
reminds me, I actually

00:51:18.330 --> 00:51:23.680
have some instructional CDs
for kids and teens on this,

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:27.430
from morethansound.net,
if anybody's interested.

00:51:27.430 --> 00:51:29.200
Because I think
it's very important

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:33.230
that parents do this for
kids and that schools do it

00:51:33.230 --> 00:51:35.190
for kids.

00:51:35.190 --> 00:51:39.000
The more you do it, the better
you get at cognitive control.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:42.770
Then you asked about chaotic
childhood and all of that.

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:44.120
And that is a negative factor.

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:46.703
That's why I was so impressed
by the school in Spanish Harlem.

